metadata.name: Kyma #26
metadata.description:
Kyma (/kee-ma/, κύμα) is a Greek word meaning wave. It is my exploration of an acoustic phenomenon known as ‘Chladni Patterns’. 

Ernst Florens Friedrich Chladni was a German physicist and musician. He was a pioneer of modern acoustics and made numerous contributions to the field. Chladni's work had a significant influence on the development of modern music theory and the technology of musical instruments. In 1787, Chladni was trying to understand how sound waves propagate and interact with objects. By vibrating a metal plate and sprinkling sand on it, he observed that the sand arranged itself into distinct patterns. These patterns are created due to the interaction between the sound waves and the plate: the sound waves cause the plate to vibrate, which in turn causes the sand to move. The sand will move away from areas of high vibration and towards areas of low vibration. This creates a unique pattern of ridges, circles, and many other shapes.

Kyma continues this study by adding color, light, and composition to the equation. Each iteration is a unique combination of two Chladni plates with different characteristics, accompanied by a palette, background lighting, and variational drawing algorithm. Plates interact with each other, forming patterns from the small detailed net-like grid to megalithic sculptures of unknown creatures and windows to another worlds.

Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Rendering can be computationally heavy, please be patient and give it some time to draw.
Chrome is highly recommended for live mode and high res saving.

Made with love, math, and p5js. 

Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2400 x 1600
[2] - save PNG 4800 x 3200
[3] - save PNG 9600 x 6400
[4] - save PNG 14400 x 9600

metadata.name: GEOMORPHISM #49
metadata.description:
A 4444 character magic spell for my rayhatching framework to render thinking rocks.

This piece may take some time to render (about 1-3 minutes, depending on hardware). The rendering time is symbolic of the vastness and agelessness of these rock structures, it is recommended to use the rendering time to contemplate deeply the concept of time spans so incredibly long, that to experience them they would have to overwrite your memories several times and thus are impossible to truly comprehend.

To ponder how, if they are so old, how come some of them float? Are these rocks the fixtures and has time and space itself eroded around them?

This project uses an approach called "rejection sampling". This means the program generates a random set of parameters, and then checks/previews how the resulting image would look. It measures the amount of visible objects, light and shadows, and then determines whether these fall into acceptable ranges. If not, it generates a new set of parameters. For certain hashes over a 100 parameter sets may be checked before it accepts the image.

The features of this project are "cliff", "ground", "thing" and "sky". These are not parameters, they are actual measurements of the resulting image, indicating what percentage of the view is occupied.

This piece can be saved as an SVG and plotted. It is recommended to run a path order optimization tool such as vpype or axicli, this will greatly reduce plotting time.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&w=.25 : The line width in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.

The line width is set to 0.25 millimetres to suit most common fine liner pen stroke widths when plotting. 

If you don't intend to plot this piece, perhaps also try rendering it at 0.2 or even 0.1 millimetres line width, for an even more detailed image (it will also take longer to render).

(c) 2022 by Piter Pasma

metadata.name: Minima #184
metadata.description:
Minima is a study on focus and color. Playing with the idea of a simple composition of semicircles, either rotated up or down. The focus of the observer is moved with the use of gradual animation in the gradients and occasional circles and/or rectangles connecting the shapes together through color.

The name minima stems from the origins of the composition, mostly taking inspiration from minimalism in its use of a few elements to form a composition greater than the sum of its parts. Less is more, as they say.

The point at the bottom right of the canvas resembles the end of a sentence. Like reading a book, you process the canvas in a similar way, moving from what pops the most to what the least.

As the reader of this canvas I hope you observe what happens to your focus as the colors gradually move across the screen. The animations themselves are looping based on a noised sine wave, which gives them imperfections, imperfections you can observe.

----

Click / Tap on the bar at the bottom of the canvas to open up the GUI, used to export your minima into any format you want. Either .png or .svg. Ready for printing, if you desire.

ps. there might be a secret keyboard shortcut...

----

Minima,
Wouter Missler, 2022,
p5js + webgl.

metadata.name: Esagoni #124
metadata.description:
A piece stepping away from control and leaning into minimalism, there are several factors at play to make your Esagoni unique. Both of the two hexagon colors are a random RGB value, at various luminosities.

The root of separation chooses which color takes the lead, between 1-100, 50 being evenly distributed.

The separation between the two colors can vary from 0-100, 0 is a 1% chance.

Modifiers can be either Circular or Hexagonal.

The scale of the hexagons on the grid varies from 1-100.

There is a 10% chance of a monochrome Esagoni, 5% respectively to both "Black on White" and "White on Black."


This piece can also be changed to infinite resolutions, for any frame or screen you'd like to display it on.

In live view, press:

'w' to view in 16:9

't' to view in 8x10

's' to view in 1x1

'f' to adapt to your own screen size

Double-click to save image

Enjoy :)

metadata.name: Allégories booléennes #425
metadata.description:
"Allégories booléennes" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

This work is a continuation of research around the intersections of shapes that I have been exploring for a while. I wonder about the way in which they make it possible to bring out new compositions from superpositions of shapes that could initially represent a real disorder.

Controls:
• "a": Play the animation
• "s": Export the image (default 2160 × 3840px PNG)
• "h": Change export settings to high resolution (then press "s" to export a 6480 ×11520px PNG)
• "m": Change export settings to medium resolution (then press "s" to export a 4320 × 7680px PNG)
• "n": Back to 2160 × 3840px

Artwork by Julien Espagnon, 2022.

metadata.name: .cloths (Japan color) #30
metadata.description:
For this Token, I was inspired by Japanese culture and incorporated colors traditionally associated with Japan into the palette.

The traditional Japanese colors, regularly tiled, resemble the scales of Nishikigoi or the patterns of a kimono (furisode) patterns.

The shearing deformation of the tile shapes; shear() makes the colors appear abstract.

The palette is selected from one of the following variations.

01. Ninja(忍者)　02. Tsukimi(月見)　03. Fuji & Moon(富士と月)　04. Urushi(漆)　05. Red Fuji(赤富士)　06. Tonosama(殿様)　07. Daimyo(大名)　08. Cherry Blossom(桜)　09. Autumn Leaves(紅葉)　10. Furisode(振り袖)　11. Nishikigoi(錦鯉)　12. Uji Kintoki(宇治金時)　13. Samurai(侍)

I would be happy if you could feel the beauty of Japan, my birthplace, even a little.



Generative art by @ConatusLab

Built in Javascript with p5.js.

Press 's(S)' to save a png.

metadata.name: Fleur des Sinus #111
metadata.description:
Originally based on Alberto Burri's 1973- 1976 Screen Prints, then further iterated upon: Fleur des Sinus is meant to play with abstraction by designing larger than the canvas. Creating something that's clearly defined and pushing in just enough to find new compositions in section and intersection.

There are two possible modes, changing the shape of the flowers.
26 palettes are available, each composed of 4 colors: 104 colors in total.
A palette is picked for each edge flower, the center flower expresses itself with no inhibitions.
The Flowers are made up of between 4-10 petals.
The background pattern is 1-6 petal minimal dot flower patterns.

Press 's' to save the image in Live View.

metadata.name: Liminal Slippage #11
metadata.description:
Is this a metaphor of thoughts and perceptions slipping in and out the threshold of the mind? Or colours and shapes bleeding into a virtual focus, gaining grain in the process?

At least we know it's two passes through two different GLSL shaders, where simplex noise is computed and reinterpreted in multiple ways.

Press [spacebar] to toggle play/pause.

When paused, press [p] to create hi-res PNG.
